Dlamini-Zuma together with other ANCWL leaders visited several households, listening to people's concerns and promising to make sure government assists them. JOHANNESBURG - African National Congress (ANC) presidential hopeful Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma says those who think she is playing politics by campaigning in Tshwane on Friday are being mischievous.Dlamini-Zuma was speaking at one of the houses visited by the ANC Women s League (ANCWL) during its door-to-door campaign.She is seen as one of the front-runners for the ANC's presidential race and has been endorsed by others as the next president for the party and the country. Dlamini-Zuma together with other ANCWL leaders visited several households, listening to people's concerns and promising to make sure government assists them.#ANCWLRally Nkosazana Dlamini Zuma is here. WATCH pic.twitter.com/jmwhGMQbP6But the former African Union commission chair says her campaigning in Tshwane has nothing to do with playing politics. They may say it, but they ll be mischievous because whenever I ve been in South Africa I ve been everywhere. Even when I was at Home Affairs I use to go around to all the offices whenever I can. I didn t join the ANC for 2019. She says whatever happens in 2019, she will continue to work towards ensuring people get a better life.She also made a turn at one of the local schools and delivered sanitary products, urging pupils to study hard and get educated.(Edited by Zamangwane Shange)